(247, 'kalio documentation', ' \r\nREFERENCES\r\nVERSION 1.0\r\nJUNE 22, 2016\r\n \r\nDeveloper References\r\nIntro to Kalio\r\nKalio Commerce is an ecommerce Content Management System. The Kalio interface is designed as a site manager and there is no direct FTP access to the web files. This CMS is built using .NET framework which is extended via their API. The API allows us to develop controls and interact with product data that resides inside Kalioâ€™s database.\r\nSupport\r\nBecause this system is designed to use Kalioâ€™s proprietary code, there are little (to no) online resources that will assist in code development. There are three main sources for code reference and support:\r\n1.	Pre-existing code which is found in â€œControlsâ€\r\n2.	In the API Documentation (although inconstancies have been identified): you can access this by logging into Kalio Site Manager and visiting Display>API Documentation\r\n3.	Kalio Support Portal: https://na3.salesforce.com/sserv/login.jsp?orgId=00D500000007JZJ\r\na.	You can submit a ticket to ask custom questions and delegate projects (These are either included or will incur additional fees)\r\nb.	You can review the â€œFind Solutionâ€ Keynotes and videos (recommended)\r\nThe â€œKalioâ€ Code\r\nThe Kalio code, also referred to as â€œD-M-Iâ€ code, is verbose by nature. For example to make a simple conditional statement within the scope of an object, you would write something such as:\r\n[[DMI:Use dmisource=''Core.GetProductByProductNumber("38610", false, true)'']]\r\n[[DMI:If dmisource=''Container.DataItem'' expression=''1 == 1'']]\r\n[[DMI:Then]]\r\n[[DMI:Property name=''ProductNumber'']][[/DMI:Property]]\r\n[[/DMI:Then]]\r\n[[/DMI:If]]\r\n[[/DMI:Use]]\r\nKalio recognized that the code aesthetics were subpar and made adjustments with the core structure. Over time, Iâ€™ve been rewriting the code to take advantage of the new structure. This is an ongoing project that is done to consolidate code and improve readability. To demonstrate an example, we can now write the above example like:\r\n\r\n\r\n<dmi:loop dmisource=''Core.GetProductByProductNumber("38610", false, true)''>\r\n<dmi:if dmisource=''Container.DataItem'' expression=''1 == 1''>\r\n<dmi:then>\r\n	<dmi:property name=''ProductNumber'' />\r\n</dmi:then>\r\n</dmi:if>\r\n</dmi:loop>\r\nRecommended resource: "Ask the Architect" Session Topic: Overview of our upcoming KalioCommerce Release: \r\nhttps://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/kalio-commerce/customer-support/Ask+the+Architect+-+Overview+of+our+upcoming+KalioCommerce+Release.wmv\r\n\r\nPage Structure\r\nThe website is comprised of both dynamic and static web pages. This said, you can navigate to the web pages by visiting the following path within Kalio: Display>Pages\r\nFor this example, find â€œproductâ€ page within the results \r\n(Note: you can search by any field at the top of the table which is made available through â€œColumn Chooserâ€)\r\nA page is made up of 4 major parts:\r\n1.	Layout: Kalio intention was to offer this to dictate different layouts (such as single column, double column, etc) per page. Since responsive conversion, Iâ€™ve converted every page to use the same layout. Iâ€™m handling the column layout within the controls which offers more flexibility when developing individual pages.\r\n2.	Placeholders:\r\n3.	Controls:\r\n4.	Header Definition:\r\nâ€ƒ\r\nContent Manager References\r\nGateway Page\r\nThis feature is attribute driven and is primarily controlled through the category section within (Kalio) Site Manager.\r\nInstruction: Log into Kalio Site Manager and visit the category. Click on Attributes (on the left) and add attributes to build and manage the Gateway Page for any category.\r\nThere are (4) attributes that influence this feature:\r\n1.	GatewayPage (True/False): This attribute controls whether the category should be treated as a category/gateway page. By setting this to true, the system will:\r\na.	Dynamically build a Gateway Page for the category by listing all sub-categories associated with this category\r\nb.	Automatically switch the main menu link to the Gateway Page\r\nc.	Automatically add the correct SEO canonical to point to the equivalent category page\r\n2.	GatewayImage (relative path starting from the image directory. Ex: â€œxl/38618.jpgâ€): This attribute tells the feature what image to use for the thumbnail for the sub-categories. This attribute should be added to ANY category that is a sub-category of any gateway category (set above)\r\n3.	GatewayPageHeaderImage (relative path starting from the image directory. Ex: â€œart/ams_gw_header.jpgâ€): This attribute tells the feature to use an enhanced custom header. If this is not set, the Gateway Page will default to the original header.\r\n4.	YoutubeVideo (the youtube video ID): If set, this attribute features a video on the Gateway Page which should pertain to the category as a whole. It adds an additional block next to â€œShop Allâ€ which functions as a callout to the video. \r\nProduct Group Page\r\n[description]\r\nInstruction: [instruction]\r\nThere are (x) attributes that influence this feature:\r\n1.	[variables] \r\n\r\n', '', 3),
