(295, 'security measures', '\r\n1. Update your website(s). Update content management systems such as WordPress to the current stable version. This is good practice because out-of-date software is leading cause of infections. This includes your CMS version, plugins, themes, and any other extension type. \r\n2. It is possible that vital files necessary to the operation of your site were infected with malware and are no longer viable or present. These may need to be replaced with clean versions of the files from newly implemented assets (themes, plugins, etc) or backups.\r\n3. Remove unneeded software such as old CMS installations, themes, and plugins. All unattended applications contribute to clutter and vulnerabilities. Take a minute to separate test, staging, and production server users and folders.\r\n4. Run a virus scan on your personal computer. Please, take a minute to run an antivirus scan. Avast, MSE, Spybot, or MalwareBytes are all free and robust antivirus products. If your personal computer is not clean, it does not matter how many times you remove malware from your website because the site can get become easily reinfected. \r\n5. Start doing backups of your site. After the site is clean and secure, a very good practice is to do daily backups at a minimum. There are number of backup solutions out there you can use. \r\n6. Update Accounts and Passwords \r\n(Tip: Start using a password manager such as Peguta and LastPass). Choose strong passwords to increase security. \r\n- Change your FTP, SFTP (or SSH) password. Change login credentials for the AccountCenter and control panels (Plesk/CPanel).\r\n- Change your CMS administrator password. If you are using WordPress, Joomla, osCommerce, or any CMS, change your administrator password. Take a minute to check and verify you know all the users in your panel. Clean up accounts by removing users with unnecessary admin privileges and force password resets for all users. \r\nWordPress users: http://codex.wordpress.org/Resetting_Your_Password \r\n- Change your database password. Some CMSs require configuration file updates Ã¢â‚¬â€œ Joomla: configuration.php and WordPress: wp-config.php. This is not an automated process so you will need to know how to open those files and edit manually.\r\n7. Review the general security resources are provided in this article: https://mediatemple.net/community/products/dv/204645260/security-resources. Depending on your site and hosting platform, there may be additional steps you can take to secure your content.\r\n', '', 3),
