(300, 'forteworks site upgrade', 'https://help.smallbusiness.yahoo.net/s/article/ka21a0000009YnxAAE/SLN20611\r\n\r\n//You cannot install because WordPress 4.7.4 requires MySQL version 5.0 or higher. You are running version 4.1.14\r\n//You cannot install because WordPress 4.2-RC1 requires MySQL version 5.0 or higher. You are running version 4.1.14.\r\n//MySQL v 4.1.14\r\n//PHP   v 5.2.12\r\n//WP \r\n \r\n\r\nHow can I upgrade from MySQL version 4 to 5?\r\n\r\nSOLUTION\r\nWe''ve updated the Small Business platform to support MySQL 5. If you''re using a database with your site or store, we recommend that you upgrade to take advantage of better performance and enhanced features.\r\n\r\nIn order to migrate to the latest version of MySQL, first make sure you''re running PHP 5.3.6 or above. To find out which version you''re running and to upgrade, visit the Create & Update tab of your Web Hosting Control Panel. Learn more about switching PHP versions.\r\n\r\nWhen you are ready to upgrade:\r\n\r\nOn the Create & Update or Index tabs of your Web Hosting Control Panel, click the MySQL Database link. \r\nClick Upgrade Database. \r\nA confirmation window will appear. Click Continue to proceed with the migration process.\r\n  Note: During the upgrade process, features of your site or store that rely on a database, such as blog comments or real-time inventory checks, will not be available to your customers.\r\n\r\nMySQL will upgrade in the background. To view the status of your upgrade, click Refresh Status. Note that most upgrades will take only a few minutes but could take longer depending on the size of your database. \r\nWhen your upgrade is complete, be sure to review your site for any issues as soon as possible. You''ll have 30 days to roll back your changes in case you encounter any problems with your upgraded database.', '', 3),
(301, 'website redirects', 'https://css-tricks.com/redirect-web-page/\r\n\r\nHow to:\r\n<meta http-equiv="refresh" content="0; URL=''http://new-website.com''" />\r\n-----------------------------------------------------------------------------\r\njavascript\r\nwindow.location = "http://new-website.com";\r\n\r\nor\r\n\r\nwindow.location = "http://new-website.com";\r\nwindow.location.href = "http://new-website.com";\r\nwindow.location.assign("http://new-website.com");\r\nwindow.location.replace("http://new-website.com");\r\n\r\nThere are a few problems here:\r\n\r\nJavaScript needs to be enabled and downloaded/executed for this to work at all.\r\nIt''s not clear how search engines react to this.\r\nThere are no status codes involved, so you can''t rely information about the redirect.\r\n-----------------------------------------------------------\r\n\r\n.htaccess\r\nRedirect 301 / http://www.new-website.com\r\n\r\n-----------------------------------------------------\r\nNGINX\r\nserver {\r\n  listen 80;\r\n  server_name old-website.com;\r\n  return 301 $scheme://new-website.com$request_uri;\r\n}\r\n---------------------------------------------\r\nPHP\r\n<?php\r\n  header(''Location: http://www.new-website.com/'', true, 301);\r\n  exit();\r\n?>\r\n--------------------------------------\r\n\r\nhttps://www.addedbytes.com/articles/for-beginners/url-rewriting-for-beginners/\r\nRewriteEngine On    # Turn on the rewriting engine\r\nRewriteRule    ^pet-care/?$    pet_care_info_01_02_2008.php    [NC,L]    # Handle requests for "pet-care"\r\n', '', 3),
