(562, 'wordpress wp migration process', 'WP-Migration-Process.txt\r\nPath A:\r\n  Plugin:\r\n    Pros: 5-10 minutes\r\nPath B:\r\n  Git:\r\n    Pros: Automatic Deployment\r\n    Cons: git, set up time\r\n\r\nFree SiteGround hosting\r\n  learnwebcode.com/studenthosting/\r\n  sign up:\r\n  $0.00\r\n  email confirmation\r\n  login, u , p\r\n  decide later option\r\n\r\nPLAN A: Process Explanation\r\nwebsite on local dev:\r\n  admin dashboard\r\n    plugin: "all-in-one WP migration"\r\n    options in side bar\r\n      exports:\r\n      export to ...file...\r\n      one file with entire website and database\r\nback to server host:\r\n  it''s admin\r\n    install "all-in-one WP migration " plugin\r\n      import...\r\n\r\nPLAN B:\r\n  Part 1: Database\r\n    to delete every thing...selects everything inside the wp folder and deletes\r\n    to delete database: mysql DB: delete\r\n    clean slate:\r\n    we need to do a Find and Replace:\r\n    Local Dev:\r\n      install plugin: "WP Migrate DB" by Delicious Brains\r\n      Tools options:\r\n        Export File with Find and Replace parameters\r\n        export(''click'')\r\n      .sql.gz file in downloads\r\n\r\n    Production Host:\r\n      cPanel home:;\r\n        go to my databases:\r\n        create empty DB:\r\n        import file we just created via\r\n        PHPMyAdmin > import\r\n\r\n  Part 2: Files\r\n    DIFF > login credentials:\r\n      check wp-config.php\r\n        he writes in a condition to check environment: local vs production.\r\n          if local.php exists\r\n          then I think he uses .gitignore on production version.\r\n    Authentication Unique Keys and Salts...\r\n    Security Update:\r\n\r\n    Then he creates git repo from DIR that contains "app" dir and gulpfile.js and siblings.\r\n    He put a private BitBucket repo.\r\n    inside of "app" dir , local.php , needs to be added to .gitignore. (and removes it temporarily).\r\n    app/local.php ~ add this line to your .gitignore\r\n\r\n    commit\r\n    push\r\n\r\n    then replace local.php  once all is set up properly.\r\n\r\n    3rd Party Deployment:\r\n      DeployHQ(free), DeployBot, FTPloy(free)\r\n      DeployHQ directions:\r\n        New Project...\r\n        go to bitbucket...\r\n          create project ...\r\n          grant access...\r\n             select repo to associate\r\n            create server ...\r\n            protocol: SFTP ssh\r\n            configs:\r\n            hostname: your siteground domain name   ftp.<here>.\r\n            port: 18765\r\n            go to cPanel > FTP accounts > username\r\n            click use SSH key\r\n            DeployHQ will give us an SSH key\r\n            Go to Siteground CPanel > SSH/shell access\r\n            go to ''upload key'' area ..\r\n\r\n            back to deployHQ : deployment path:\r\n            for siteground the deployment path = public_html/\r\n            branch to deploy from : dev, stage, live, production, etc...\r\n            sub dir to deploy from: app/ '' or wherever your wp files are...''\r\n\r\n            New Deployment\r\n            first do it manually...\r\n            click deploy.\r\n\r\n            MAKE SURE DB USER has been added to the DB used.\r\n\r\n            ''AUTOMATIC setup'':\r\n            At DeployHQ:\r\n            servers > (edit pencil icon)\r\n            ''Enable auto deployments''\r\n            copy the URL webhook.\r\n            need to include this in repo...\r\n            back to bitbucket...> settigs > webhooks > add webhook > add url\r\n            ''check to see it works''...\r\n\r\n            upon commit and push ----auto deployed !!!!\r\n\r\n            \r\n', '', 3),
