(661, 'Continuous Delivery for Wordpress', 'Started with looking into AWS Pipeline:\r\nhttps://docs.aws.amazon.com/codepipeline/latest/userguide/welcome.html\r\n\r\nHere is some research on Wordpress and Continuous Delivery.\r\nWhile looking for a walkthrough for wordpress and AWS Pipeline, which I still havenâ€™t found yet , I \r\nCame across  AWS CodeDeploy and â€˜CodeShipâ€™ which looks like a good option as well.\r\n\r\nAWS CodeDeploy vs AWS Pipeline\r\n\r\n1) AWS CodeDeploy and Codeship\r\n https://aws.amazon.com/codedeploy/product-integrations/codeship/\r\nhttps://blog.codeship.com/aws-codedeploy-codeship/\r\n\r\n2) Setting up simple Wordpress deployment with CodeShip to AWS EC2\r\nhttps://blog.eq8.eu/article/setting-up-simple-wordpres-deployment-with-codeship-to-aws-ec2.html\r\n\r\nAWS Pipeline\r\nThis is the process but without wordpress.\r\n3) https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dAjhe_0DC-Q\r\n\r\n4) AWS and CircleCI: Self-Hosted Continuous Integration may require using GitHub\r\nhttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=m4plGZmZkj4\r\n\r\ninteresting aside:\r\nhttps://codecanyon.net/item/wpjenkins-simply-run-jenkins-jobs-through-wordpress/20855474\r\n\r\n', '', 3),
