(671, 'AWS Cloudfront CDN and Wordpress ', 'AWS Cloudfront CDN and Wordpress \r\nBrief:\r\n	1) IAM access\r\n	2) Buckets\r\n		- access and permissions( bucket policies )\r\n	3) Cloudfront Distributions\r\n		-Behaviors for different content locations\r\n\r\n \r\nFor details on a ''Wordpress'' specific configuration of AWS Cloudfront,\r\nread this.\r\nHow to accelerate your WordPress site with Amazon CloudFront\r\nby Ronan Guilfoyle | on 06 NOV 2017\r\nhttps://aws.amazon.com/blogs/startups/how-to-accelerate-your-wordpress-site-with-amazon-cloudfront/\r\n\r\nVideos:\r\n\r\n1) Strictly AWS Approach:\r\n"Cloudfront for Wordpress"\r\nhttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yv7zS3fJE3E\r\n\r\n2) Plugin Approach\r\nAWS Cloudfront and WP Total Cache\r\nhttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yaFt3lUvsH8', '', 3),
(672, 'thinkful hints for beginners', '1)\r\nget ''google chrome  browser'' on your computer.\r\nopen Developer tools....ctrl + shift + i \r\nopen ''console  tab'' and start to code.\r\n\r\n2) \r\nhave html, js, and css files in a dir on your computer and just \r\nopen them...with R-click in File Explorer or Finder.\r\nOnce you have this open in your ''developer tools''\r\nand learn to use ''Edit as HTML'' and to ''alter css properties'' and to \r\nwrite javascript in the console.\r\n\r\n\r\n3) HTML \r\nstructure , nesting\r\n\r\n4) css\r\nborder: dotted 1px red; /* to layout elements */\r\n\r\n5) Javascript\r\nlet name = "Joe";\r\nconsole.log(name);\r\nlet x = 2; \r\nlet y = 3;\r\nconsole.log(x + y);\r\n\r\n6) Understanding the Thinkful Resources:\r\nHaving a repl.it account and ''forking'' code examples from ''Thinkful'' over to your account.\r\n\r\nUsing a ''gist'' account to store your work and code snippets.\r\n\r\n7) Programming: Is like reading and or writing  ''recipes''.\r\nThe goal might be to write a function that makes biscuits. The first time you write the function \r\nand you figure out what ingredients and steps you need to take to make biscuits. But in the future, once the work is done, you should be able to call the ''biscuits'' function , and just simply get one in return.\r\n\r\n8) Salsa... and recursively or iteratively... first you put in the basic ingredients...tomatoes, onions, etc...then you stop and taste it. Then you go back and add some salt. Stir it up and stop and taste it again. If it''s too salty you add water, if it''s not salty enough , you add more salt, otherwise you move on to the next ingredient.\r\nThe ''iteration'' is going back and tasting the results after every few steps.\r\nThe ''condition'' is deciding whether to ''add water'' , ''add more salt'', or ''move on to another ingredient''.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n', '', 3),
