(707, 'xcode reduce size', '1) ---\r\nAlthough it''s not directly related to the Xcode app size. There are multiple places where you can delete files to free up some space.\r\n\r\n1. Derived Data Xcode keeps data about your projects which includes index, build output and logs. Go to ~/Library/Developer/Xcode/DerivedData/ and delete the folders for projects that you no longer need to keep this data around for.\r\n\r\n2. iOS Device Support Xcode is storing information about the devices you have used for development. Delete the data no longer needed in ~/Library/Developer/Xcode/iOS DeviceSupport/.\r\n\r\n3. Archives Delete the oneâ€™s you donâ€™t need in the Organizer, or go to ~/Library/Developer/Xcode/Archives/ to delete them in bulk. Be careful not to delete archives for which you still need the dSYM data for debugging.\r\n\r\n4. Simulators Simulators are stored under ~/Library/Developer/CoreSimulator/Devices. For each version of iOS you are building for.\r\n\r\n5. Documentation Browse and delete unnecessary data under ~/Library/Developer/Shared/Documentation/DocSets.\r\n2)---\r\nGrand Perspective app and \r\nHereâ€™s how to do it:\r\n\r\nRight-click one of the big files GrandPerspective found â€“ it will be called dyld_shared_cache_arm64 â€“ and choose Reveal In Finder.\r\nIn Finder, hold down the Cmd key and press the Up cursor key a few times until you finally have a folder called â€œiOS DeviceSupportâ€ selected.\r\nGo back into that folder and youâ€™ll see it has directories for iOS version numbers, e.g. 9.3.5 (13G36), 10.3.2 (14F89), and 10.3.3 (14G60).\r\nSelect all of them, delete them, then empty the trash.\r\nPlug in your iOS devices then launch Xcode so it can download the symbols you actually need.\r\nFeel smug.', '', 3),
(708, 'ObjectiveC Real Projects', 'At Indatus:\r\nI recommended we start programming mobile apps.\r\nFirst we created an app for Kindred.\r\nSandeep, started figuring out how to program in Objective C and I shadowed along with him. \r\nWe did a ''survey'' type app for Derby. \r\nWe did an app for Sacred Heart, for them to screen prospective students. \r\nWe created a ''bourbon trail'' app.\r\nWe worked on an app for an insurance company to assess damage in areas affected by natural disasters. This would allow people in the effected area to take photos at specific geo-locations and describe the damage.\r\n\r\nI became familiar with the process of submitting an app to itunes as well as deploying it from \r\na Mobile Device Managent system , Maas360.\r\n\r\nI became familiar with key coding elements such as\r\nCoreData with object models and configuring relationships between tables.\r\nMutli-Threading, to keep UI separated from API work.\r\nUsing their interface builder.\r\nLinking to API''s and parsing XML responses.\r\n\r\n\r\nI also created my own app called ''Core Keeper'' and had it on itunes for a while.\r\nHere it is on some miscellaneous website:\r\nhttp://appcrawlr.com/ios/core-keeper-math\r\nI made the mistake of linking it to an API that eventual got moved, so the app lost its dynamic functionailty.\r\n\r\nAfter Indatus, I had little to no exposure to Objective C work professionally but retain a fondness for working with it. Since then I have seen Javascript evolve into NodeJS, ReactJS, Angular 4, and have been primarily concerned with web based technology. \r\n\r\n\r\nI still have a library of snippets that I kept while learning objective C here.\r\nThis was created back in 2014.\r\nhttp://www.forteworks.com/00toolbox/v/ \r\nhttp://www.forteworks.com/00toolbox/c/TableViewController.php\r\n\r\nas well as some Android related study.\r\n\r\n\r\n----note from Brian Brown:\r\nWe did a survey for \r\nDoc Crows restaurant, \r\nDonan Engineering, \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n', '', 3),
