(590, '\r\n RWD:\r\n Bootstrap RWD:\r\n http://www.sitepoint.com/responsive-web-design-tips-bootstrap-css/\r\n take away:\r\n CONTAINERS:\r\n  .container has different widths for different types of devices \r\n  whereas \r\n  .container-fluid expands to fit the width of the device.\r\n  COLUMNS:\r\n  A class .col-lg-6 will have a width of 50% in large devices but when viewed in medium, small, and extra-small devices, the default width: auto is used. This ensures that the columns are converted to a stacked layout (rather than side by side) in smaller devices.\r\n  TABLES:\r\n  .table --forces tables to fit the width of the parent element by applying a width of 100%.\r\n  and \r\n  .table-reponsive --cause the table to become scrollable on the horizontal axis on smaller devices\r\n  .table-responsive {\r\n  width: 100%;\r\n  overflow-x: auto;\r\n  overflow-y: hidden;\r\n  -webkit-overflow-scrolling: touch;\r\n  -ms-overflow-style: -ms-autohiding-scrollbar;\r\n  border: 1px solid #ddd;\r\n}\r\nIMAGES:\r\n.img-responsive --ensure the images scale down proportionally in smaller devices, while staying within the parent elementâ€™s constraints on larger devices\r\n.img-responsive {\r\n  display: block;\r\n  max-width: 100%;\r\n  height: auto;\r\n}\r\nTYPOGRAPHY:\r\nOn the web the use of EM''s in typography (and also element widths and media queries) are based upon the root pixel value.  This is done by setting the html or body tag to font-size: 16px; which aligns with what most (all) browsers set as the default font size. \r\n\r\nThis means that 1em = 16px, 5em = 80px, 37.5em = 600px, 60em = 960px etc etc.\r\n	Margins,Padding and LIne Height too:\r\nWhen you set your margins and padding around your typographic elements (p, blockquote, h1-h6, li etc) be sure to keep them as EM measurements... and don''t forget to maintain the same rules when it comes to line-height.', 'RWD: responsive web design tips and best practice notes.', 'css'),
(591, 'import flash.text.TextField;\r\nimport flash.text.TextFormat;\r\n//TUTORIAL: http://www.republicofcode.com/tutorials/flash/as3text/\r\n\r\n//basic\r\n/*\r\nvar  myText:TextField = new TextField();\r\nmyText.text = "The quick red fox jumps over the lazy dog.";\r\naddChild(myText);\r\nmyText.textColor = 0xFF0000;\r\nmyText.border = true;\r\nmyText.wordWrap = true;\r\nmyText.width = 150;\r\nmyText.height = 50;\r\nmyText.x = 100;\r\nmyText.y = 100;\r\n*/\r\n//------------------------------------------\r\n// Using the TextFormat CLass\r\n	// USING EMBEDDED FONTS\r\n \r\n//This step involved selecting a font from the library, exporting it as actionscript...\r\nvar myFont = new Font1();\r\n\r\n//1) the format class\r\nvar myFormat:TextFormat = new TextFormat();\r\nmyFormat.size = 25;\r\nmyFormat.font = myFont.fontName;\r\n//alignment options:\r\n	//myFormat.align = TextFormatAlign.CENTER;\r\n	//CENTER, LEFT, RIGHT , JUSTIFY\r\n//2 then the textField\r\nvar  myText:TextField = new TextField();\r\n// important step to declare textfields default format class.\r\nmyText.defaultTextFormat = myFormat;\r\n//---add these 2 lines for fonts to work\r\nmyText.embedFonts = true;\r\nmyText.antiAliasType = AntiAliasType.ADVANCED;\r\n//\r\nmyText.text = "The quick red fox jumps over the lazy dog.";\r\naddChild(myText);\r\nmyText.textColor = 0xFF0000;\r\nmyText.border = true;\r\nmyText.wordWrap = true;\r\nmyText.width = 150;\r\nmyText.height = 50;\r\nmyText.x = 100;\r\nmyText.y = 100;\r\n', 'actionscript: text formatting:: TextField and TextFormat ', 'javascript'),
